  description="Pool renovation on the Gold Coast — coping replacement, paving surround, glass fence integration, structural crack repair, leak detection. QBCC-licensed."
  canonical="https://goldcoastpoolbuilders.com.au/services/pool-renovation/">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Coping &middot; surround &middot; structural &middot; integration</span>
      <h1>Pool renovation across the <span class="accent">Gold Coast</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        The full make-it-look-new package short of a complete resurface or rebuild
        &mdash; coping replacement, surround paving, glass fence retrofit,
        structural crack repair, leak detection, equipment relocation. Often the
        most cost-effective option when the pool surface itself is still sound.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61485939966">&#9742; Call 0485 939 966</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book a free on-site quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Renovation services we offer.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">

        <h3>Coping replacement.</h3>
        <p>
          The coping is the edge stone where the pool wall meets the surround.
          Original 1990s pools usually have <strong>concrete bullnose coping</strong>
          that&rsquo;s now chipped, cracked, and showing efflorescence. Modern
          replacement options:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Travertine bullnose:</strong> Warm cream tone, slip-resistant. Cool underfoot in QLD heat. $180&ndash;$280/lineal metre. The current Gold Coast standard.</li>
          <li><strong>Bluestone / basalt bullnose:</strong> Modern dark grey, contemporary look. $220&ndash;$320/lin m.</li>
          <li><strong>Limestone bullnose (Sareen, Crema):</strong> Soft white, beachy. Heats up more in direct sun. $200&ndash;$300/lin m.</li>
          <li><strong>Drop-edge / rebated coping:</strong> Modern flush-look with hidden water line. Premium. $280&ndash;$420/lin m.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Surround paving upgrade.</h3>
        <p>
          The 1980s&ndash;2000s default surround was stamped concrete or pavers
          on sand &mdash; both shift over time and grow weeds in the joints. Modern
          replacement: <strong>travertine, bluestone, porcelain or natural stone
          tile on a concrete slab with adhesive set</strong>. No more weeds, no
          more shifting, looks contemporary. $200&ndash;$400/m&sup2; supplied + laid.
          Typical pool surround 30&ndash;60m&sup2; = $6K&ndash;$24K.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Glass fence retrofit for Form 23 compliance.</h3>
        <p>
          Most pre-2010 pool fences are <strong>powder-coated aluminium tube
          fencing</strong>. Compliant when built but often non-compliant under
          current Queensland Development Code MP 3.4 due to: missing 900mm
          climbable zone, latch height below 1500mm, gate not self-closing
          from 0&deg;, etc. For a sale Form 23 you need full compliance. Modern
          frameless or semi-frameless glass fencing solves these issues AND
          looks better. Retrofit cost: $4K&ndash;$12K for typical surround.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Structural crack repair.</h3>
        <p>
          Hairline surface cracks (under 1mm wide) are cosmetic only and can be
          sealed during a resurface. <strong>Anything over 1mm wide</strong> or
          actively leaking water needs structural attention &mdash; epoxy
          injection from inside the shell, sometimes with an external waterproof
          patch from the surround side. $800&ndash;$5,000 depending on crack length
          and access. If you see cracking near a corner or in the floor, the
          underlying issue might be hydrostatic-uplift damage (water-table
          pressure) or settlement &mdash; we investigate before patching.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Leak detection &amp; repair.</h3>
        <p>
          Pool losing more than 5mm/day overnight (after accounting for
          evaporation) has a leak. Diagnostics:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Bucket test:</strong> rule out evaporation vs structural loss</li>
          <li><strong>Visual scan for cracks, separated tile, failed coping</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Dye test at suction and return points</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Pressure test plumbing lines</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Underground listening device for buried-pipe leaks</strong></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Most Gold Coast leaks are at <strong>plumbing fittings</strong> (skimmer
          throat, return jet, suction port) or <strong>compromised coping seal</strong>
          rather than the pool shell itself. Typical repair $400&ndash;$3,000.
          Plumbing-line leak under coping = $2K&ndash;$8K (excavate, repair, refit).
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Common combined renovation packages.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Coping + paving combo:</strong> Strip back old, lay travertine throughout. $15K&ndash;$30K.</li>
          <li><strong>Coping + glass fence + paving:</strong> Full surround makeover. $22K&ndash;$48K.</li>
          <li><strong>Resurface + coping + glass fence:</strong> Most popular full-rejuvenation package. $30K&ndash;$60K.</li>
          <li><strong>Equipment + surround + lighting:</strong> &ldquo;Modern&rdquo; without touching the pool. $12K&ndash;$25K.</li>
          <li><strong>Pre-sale Form 23 remediation:</strong> Fence + minor cosmetic. $6K&ndash;$15K.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

